{
  "answer": "**Tarāna-e-Millī**'s most explicit collective-identity claim unites all Muslims geographically into a single *millat* (Muslim community/nation): \"From Chin to Arab lands, our story flows, / The whole wide world's the home a Muslim knows.\"[^1]\n\n**Manusmṛti** Book 1's most explicit claim distributes humanity into four fixed *varṇas* (social orders) by primordial birth from the cosmic Puruṣa's body: \"for the sake of the prosperity of the worlds, he caused the Brahmana, the Kshatriya, the Vaishya, and the Shudra to emanate from his mouth, arms, thighs, and feet.\"[^2]\n\nThe asymmetry—*Tarāna-e-Millī*'s *millat* open to all via conviction in monotheism, vs. *Manusmṛti*'s *varṇas* sealed by birth—is visible in *Tarāna*'s very next stanza: \"The sacred trust of One God fills our soul, / No force can wipe our name from history's scroll,\" defining Muslim identity through indelible *faith* (not origin).[^3] *Manusmṛti* knows no such entry; duties are \"assigned\" at creation by embodiment alone.[^4]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 23 (*Tarāna-e-Millī*), [p-8a4681](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/23-tarana-e-milli/translation/#p-8a4681).\n[^2]: *Manusmṛti*, ch. 1, [p-13a2db](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-13a2db).\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 23 (*Tarāna-e-Millī*), [p-882645](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/23-tarana-e-milli/translation/#p-882645).\n[^4]: *Manusmṛti*, ch. 1, [p-26a572](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-26a572) (\"the one duty the Lord assigned to the Shudra\").",
